metadata.documentation: An AWS Elemental MediaStore container is a namespace that holds folders and objects. You use a container endpoint to create, read, and delete objects.

CreateContainer.documentation: Creates a storage container to hold objects. A container is similar to a bucket in the Amazon S3 service.

exceptions.documentation: Resource already exists or is being updated.
A service limit has been exceeded.
The service is temporarily unavailable.

DeleteContainer.documentation: Deletes the specified container. Before you make a DeleteContainer request, delete any objects in the container or in any folders in the container. You can delete only empty containers.

exceptions.documentation: Resource already exists or is being updated.
Could not perform an operation on a container that does not exist.
The service is temporarily unavailable.

DeleteContainerPolicy.documentation: Deletes the access policy that is associated with the specified container.

exceptions.documentation: Resource already exists or is being updated.
Could not perform an operation on a container that does not exist.
Could not perform an operation on a policy that does not exist.
The service is temporarily unavailable.

DescribeContainer.documentation: Retrieves the properties of the requested container. This returns a single Container object based on ContainerName. To return all Container objects that are associated with a specified AWS account, use ListContainers.

exceptions.documentation: Could not perform an operation on a container that does not exist.
The service is temporarily unavailable.

GetContainerPolicy.documentation: Retrieves the access policy for the specified container. For information about the data that is included in an access policy, see the AWS Identity and Access Management User Guide.

exceptions.documentation: Resource already exists or is being updated.
Could not perform an operation on a container that does not exist.
Could not perform an operation on a policy that does not exist.
The service is temporarily unavailable.

ListContainers.documentation:
Lists the properties of all containers in AWS Elemental MediaStore.

You can query to receive all the containers in one response. Or you can include the MaxResults parameter to receive a limited number of containers in each response. In this case, the response includes a token. To get the next set of containers, send the command again, this time with the NextToken parameter (with the returned token as its value). The next set of responses appears, with a token if there are still more containers to receive.

See also DescribeContainer, which gets the properties of one container.

exceptions.documentation: The service is temporarily unavailable.

PutContainerPolicy.documentation:
Creates an access policy for the specified container to restrict the users and clients that can access it. For information about the data that is included in an access policy, see the AWS Identity and Access Management User Guide.

For this release of the REST API, you can create only one policy for a container. If you enter PutContainerPolicy twice, the second command modifies the existing policy.

exceptions.documentation: Could not perform an operation on a container that does not exist.
Resource already exists or is being updated.
The service is temporarily unavailable.

Container.documentation: This section describes operations that you can perform on an AWS Elemental MediaStore container.

The return value does not include the container's endpoint. To make downstream requests, you must obtain this value by using DescribeContainer or ListContainers.
